supportDesc.foliation: Foliated in pencil by a modern hand.
supportDesc.condition: The flyleaves have been cut out at the front and back. Stubs left at the back.

p.note: Table of content in brown and black ink by two different modern hands. At the bottom old signum "N: 14".
A few words and signs by a medieval hand scattered over the page, probably a pen-trial.

binding.p: Late medieval binding, torn brown tanned skin over wooden boards, blind-stamped, 3 stamps: rosette and fleur-de lys of two sizes arranged within the lozenges formed from fillets, surrounded by a frame. The covering is cracked on the spine; 4 double spinebands plus endbands; 2 hook-clasp fastenings going from the lower board, upper strap detached but preserved; different catchplates at the fore-edge of the upper cover.
Old signum "89" in black ink on the middle of the spine, above which the current signum "A 35" in gold. At the bottom of the spine a lable with signum "A 35".

history.origin:
Denmark , probably Viborg diocese. The liturgical contents agree to some extant with the liturgical traditions of the Danish dioceses of Slesvig, Odense and Århus, but the highest degree of solemnity of St. Kjeld (Kettil) and the strong Augustinian features point to the diocese of Viborg, Jutland (any breviary for this diocese is not preserved). The Birgittine and Franciscan influences are obvious. The great number of saints, however, which are not found in the liturgical traditions of the Danish dioceses, might imply the martyrology (probably from Jutland) as a model for the manuscript. Furthermore, the rubrics like In cicilia natalis sanctorum lxxxiiii (), In Britania deposicio Felicis episcopi () and the obit: Hic obiit Vademarus rex Danorum by 12. May (, relating to Valdemar I ‘the Great’) could confirm this suggestion, see Helander, pp. 48-53, and Andersen, p. 103 with footnote 71. The feminine grammatical forms in both Latin prayers for Sophia (, famula) and in one in vernacular (f. 121ra ‘syndherskæ’) point to a female owner.
Dating: the feast of Catherine of Sweden implies dating after 1489, see Andersen, p. 114, and note 71, according to Chesnutt the date shortly after 1500 would be plausible.
history.provenance: Antikvitetsarkivet, listed in the old handwritten catalogues/inventories as "no. 144" (U 90:1, f. 12v); "no. 89" (U 90:2, f. 8); "G 89" (U 91:1), but changed to "35"; "no. 54" (U 91:5). Berch’s catalogue shelfmark A 35 (current signum).

no. 14 (inside cover) is possibly written by Johan Hadorph jr. and probably refers to the arrangement of the library of Antikvitetskollegiet from about 1689, cf. H. Ilsøe, ‘Antikvitetskollegiets danske håndskrifter af historisk indhold’, NTBB 55 (1968), p. 8.
history.acquisition: From Antikvitetsarkivet to the National Library.

msItem.title: Sanctorale starting in Stephen, 26 December, ending in Theodosia, 18 January.
msItem.rubric: Hic incipit de Sanctis primo de sancto stephano antiphona
msItem.incipit: Intuens in celum beatus stephanus uidit gloriam dei et ait ecce uideo celos apertos
msItem.explicit: Da nobis quesumus omnipotens deus ut sicut adoranda filii tui natalicia preuenimus sic eius munera capiamus sempiterna gaudentes Per eundem qui. theodosie virginis eodem die.

note.p: A majority of the pages contain gaps where only the rubric has been written, but no text.

A large number of feasts, some difficult to identify (e.g. f. 30v De sancto Mathia pontifice, 16. or 17. Jan.), some with erroneous rubrics; for a number of feasts there are no liturgical forms inserted. Onuphrius, er., and Sophia v. (f. 58), 11. and 15. May respectively are wrongly inserted between the octave of John Bapt. and Peter and Paul, the forms are written by two scribes which are different from a main scribe of the surrounding text; f. 54v rubric: Onofreus confessor added later. Danish saints: Knud Lavard, 7. Jan. (f. 29r), 25. June (f. 57r), see M. Chesnutt, The Medieval Danish Liturgy of St Knud Lavard, (Copenhagen, 2003), pp. 77-8; Lucius, pope, 4. March (f. 39v-40r), translation of Lucius’ head, 25. Aug. (f. 74rv, a collect not written by a main scribe); Vilhelm, abb., 16. June (f. 55r); Knud, king, m., 19 April: translacio Kanuti regis (f. 47r), 10. July (f. 61v-62r); Kjeld, conf., 11-18 July [f. 62r-64r, the antiphons, see M. Cl. Gertz, Vitae sanctorum Danorum (Copenhagen, 1908-12, pp. 279-80, 283, antiphon for first Vespers not found in Gertz, unidentified: Magnificent dominum votis . . . meritis signisque choruscum], 27. Sept.: Deposicio s. Ketilli eodem die (f. 80v-81r text not inserted); Marinus, conf., 11. July (f. 62v, text not inserted by a main scribe, the rubric In ipso die beati Ketilli eciam de sancto Marino episcopo et martire added on the margin at the head), 16. July (f. 63v); rubric Marini abbatis et martiris, 12. June, added on the margin of f. 54v; Eufrosina and Florentia, vv., 16. July (f. 63v); Thøger, conf., 30. Oct. (f. 85rv). Other Scandinavian saints: Henry, bp., m., 19. Jan. (f. 31r, text not inserted); Ansgar, bp., m., 3 Febr. (f. 34rv, concerning the text, see Helander, pp. 49-53, 68, 159-61, 253, a mixture of items called by Helander German-Danish office); Sigfrid, bp., m., 15 Febr. (f. 37rv); Halward, m., 15. May (f. 51v, text not inserted); Olaf, king, m., 29 July (f. 67v-68r); Sunniva, v., m., 7 Sept. (f. 76v); Catherine of Sweden Katerina filia beate Birgitte, 24. March (f. 44r, the form written by two scribes), see B. Carlé, A. Fröjmark, ‘Danemark – Suède – Finlande’, Hagiographies II: histoire internationale de la littérature hagiographique latine et vernaculaire en Occident des origines à 1550, Corpus Christianorum (Turnhout, 1996), p. 523 no. 14g; G. Bäärnhielm, ‘Katarina av Vadstena’, Medieval Nordic Literature in Latin, ed. H. Aili, S. Borgehammar, K. Friss-Jensen and L.B. Mortensen, in progress; Eric, king, m., 18 May (f. 52r, unknown antiphon for second Vespers: In gentibus multis non erat rex similes ei . . . super omnem Israel, identical with the chapter of Sext of Breviarium Lincopense); Eskil, m., 12. June (f. 54v); David of Munkentorp, m., 25 June (f. 57r, only the rubric); Birgitta of Sweden, 23. July (f. 65v-66r, text after the office Rosa rorans), 7 Oct. (f. 82v-83r, text after the office Birgitte matris inclite), furthermore In translacione Birgitte with only one collect is found in the additions added (f. 95r), the same feast rubric added as well on the margin of f. 53r, 26 May. Of note: Catherine of Siena, v., probably 1. May (f. 48v, between Walburga and Athanasius and Saturninus); Edmund, king, m. 2. May (f. 49r) and 20. Nov. (f. 88r, text not inserted), further, a collect among the additions (p. 97r); Monica, widow (mother of s. Augustine), 3. May (sic!) (f. 49v, placed before Invention of the Holy Cross) but a further rubric: Monice vidue eodem die, 4 May after Cyriac, bp. and before Gotthard, bp. (f. 50r); Translation of Nicolas, bp., conf. 9. May (f. 51r, only a rubric); Sophia v., 15. May (f. 58v, six collects in which praying person is called famula tua, none antiphons); Bernardino of Siena OFM, 20. May (f. 52v); Translation of Francis of Assisi, 25. May (f. 53r, only a rubric); Antony of Padua, 13 June (f. 55r) and translation 16 Febr. (f. 37v); Margaret v., m. 13. July (f. 62v, text not inserted), 20. July (ff. 64v-65r); Anna 28. July (f. 67v), and 9. Dec.; Clare, v. 12. August (f. 71v, not inserted by a main scribe); Ludwig, bp., 16 Aug. (f. 73r); Augustine of Hippo, 28 August (f. 74v-75r) with octave (f. 76v, only a rubric); Francis of Assisi, 4. Oct. (f. 82rv); Stigmata of Francis of Assisi?, 17. Sept. (f. 79r the text not inserted).
